# External vs Internal

In Swift, parameters can have **two** names: an external label (for the person calling the function) and an internal name (for use inside the function).

```swift
// 'to' is the external label. 'name' is internal.
func sendEmail(to name: String) {
    print("Sending email to \(name)..")
}

// We call it using the external label:
sendEmail(to: "Tim")
```
`sendEmail(to: "Tim")` reads exactly like an English sentence! Beautiful!

# The Magical Underscore '_'

Sometimes, you don't want a label at all when calling a function. You can use an underscore `_` as the external label to omit it entirely!

```swift
func buy(_ item: String) {
    print("You bought a \(item)")
}

// Notice there's no label here!
buy("Sword")
```
Compare `buy("Sword")` to `buy(item: "Sword")`. The first is much cleaner if the context is obvious!

